Extraction Tables
Concept 1: K'é (Kinship Solidarity)
Field	Content
1.  Tradition	Native American (Navajo/Diné)
2.  Love concept	K'é — no single English equivalent; translated variously as "respect," "friendship," "reciprocal relations," "solidarity," and "love" per Chief Justice Robert Yazzie (quoted in Austin 2009, cited in curriculum document)
3.  Core claim	K'é names the web of clan-based relational obligations that constitute the primary social bond, with the mother-child relationship as its focal standard of solidarity behavior.
4.  Mechanism	Reciprocity through giving and sharing of physical and emotional sustenance; intensity varies by sociogeographic and genealogical distance but the code (kindness, helpfulness, cooperativeness, peacefulness) applies across all kin. NOT ADDRESSED IN SOURCES: whether non-kin can be incorporated into k'é.
5.  Cost	Continuous obligation to give, share, and maintain relationships; time, resources, and emotional labor borne by all parties. NOT ADDRESSED IN SOURCES: specific quantification of cost or asymmetry in burden.
6.  Protection target	The kinship network itself—family, clan, tribe, community—and by extension the individual embedded within it. K'é is described as "the richest source of internal, external, and existential health protection" (Kahn-John & Koithan 2015).
7.  Contested?	YES. Witherspoon (1974, 1977) treats k'é as a behavioral code rooted in kinship taxonomy, while Yazzie (via Austin 2009) treats k'é as a legal/jurisprudential principle encompassing "love." Whether k'é is primarily a kinship system with affective consequences or primarily an affective/ethical principle instantiated through kinship is disputed across disciplinary boundaries (anthropology vs. Navajo legal scholarship).
