Concept 2: Hózhó (Harmony/Wellness)
Field	Content
1.  Tradition	Native American (Navajo/Diné)
2.  Love concept	Hózhó — not a love-term per se, but a state of "beauty, harmony, goodness, wellbeing, blessedness, order, and ideal" (Wyman & Haile, cited in Kahn-John & Koithan 2015) that encompasses relational wellbeing.
3.  Core claim	Hózhó is the all-inclusive positive environment that individuals strive to attain and maintain through proper thought, speech, and behavior, including the nurturing of supportive relationships.
4.  Mechanism	Six attributes: spirituality, respect, reciprocity, discipline, thinking, and relationships (Kahn-John & Koithan 2015). Reciprocal exchanges of "support, food, gifts, love, compassion, and respect" are viewed as means of maintaining relationship. Note: "love" appears here as one item in a list of relational goods, not as a separately theorized mechanism.
5.  Cost	Disciplined productive daily activity; self-care; helpfulness to others; generosity. The individual bears primary responsibility for maintaining hózhó through conscious practice.
6.  Protection target	Self, others, family, community, tribe, spirits, all living creatures, nature, and the universe—the "whole of creation" (Kahn-John & Koithan 2015).
7.  Contested?	YES. Marked with asterisk. The operationalization of hózhó in nursing/health scholarship (Kahn-John & Koithan 2015) has been criticized as potentially reductionist by Diné scholars. The 2015 article explicitly states their effort is "a humble attempt to capture the essence of this wellness philosophy held sacred by the Diné and is not meant to disrespect or reduce the meaning of this sacred Diné philosophy." Whether hózhó can be decomposed into six discrete attributes without distortion is an active methodological tension.*
