Ambiguities
•  No dedicated Navajo term for "love" as a freestanding philosophical concept. The English word "love" appears in scholarship only as a gloss for k'é or as one item in lists of relational virtues subsumed under hózhó. Whether the Navajo language contains a distinct lexeme for romantic love, parental love, or divine love is NOT ADDRESSED IN SOURCES.
•  K'é as "love" is attested only in legal/curricular secondary sources (Austin 2009, curriculum document), not in the foundational linguistic-anthropological literature (Witherspoon 1974, 1977). Witherspoon describes k'é solidarity as including "kindness, helpfulness, cooperativeness, peacefulness" and "the giving and sharing of physical and emotional sustenance"—but does not use the word "love."
Disputes
•  Anthropological vs. Indigenous legal framing: Witherspoon's structuralist analysis treats k'é as a kinship taxonomy with behavioral correlates. Navajo legal scholars (Yazzie, Austin) treat k'é as a normative jurisprudential principle that includes "love." These are not necessarily contradictory but represent different disciplinary emphases.
•  Hózhó operationalization: The decomposition of hózhó into six attributes in nursing scholarship (Kahn-John 2010, 2015) may conflict with holistic Diné epistemologies that resist analytic separation.
Protocol Problems
